'''SMS ''Goeben''''' {{efn|name=SMS}} was the second of two {{sclass-|Moltke|battlecruiser}}s of the [[Imperial German Navy]], launched in 1911 and named after the German [[Franco-Prussian War]] veteran General [[August Karl von Goeben]]. Along with her [[SMS Moltke|sister ship]], ''Goeben'' was similar to the previous German battlecruiser design, {{SMS|Von der Tann||2}}, but larger, with increased armor protection and two more main guns in an additional [[gun turret|turret]]. ''Goeben'' and ''Moltke'' were significantly larger and better armored than the comparable British {{sclass-|Indefatigable|battlecruiser|4}}.{{efn|name=cf Indefatigable}}

Several months after her commissioning in 1912, ''Goeben'', with the [[light cruiser]] {{SMS|Breslau||2}}, formed the German [[Mediterranean Division]] and patrolled there during the [[Balkan Wars]]. After the outbreak of [[World War I]] on 28 July 1914, ''Goeben'' and ''Breslau'' bombarded French positions in North Africa and then evaded British naval forces in the Mediterranean and reached [[Constantinople]]. The two ships were transferred to the [[Ottoman Empire]] on 16 August 1914, and ''Goeben'' became the flagship of the [[Ottoman Navy]] as '''''Yavuz Sultan Selim''''', usually shortened to '''''Yavuz'''''. By bombarding Russian facilities in the Black Sea, she brought Turkey into World War I on the German side. The ship operated primarily against Russian forces in the [[Black Sea]] during the war, including several inconclusive engagements with Russian [[battleship]]s. She made a sortie into the [[Aegean Sea|Aegean]] in January 1918 that resulted in the [[Battle of Imbros]], where ''Yavuz'' sank a pair of British [[monitor (warship)|monitors]] but was herself badly damaged by [[naval mine|mine]]s.

In 1936 she was officially renamed '''TCG ''Yavuz''''' ("Ship of the Turkish Republic ''Yavuz''"); she carried the remains of [[Mustafa Kemal Atatürk]] from [[Istanbul]] to [[İzmit]] in 1938. ''Yavuz'' remained the flagship of the [[Turkish Navy]] until she was decommissioned in 1950. She was scrapped in 1973, after the West German government declined an invitation to buy her back from Turkey. She was the last surviving ship built by the Imperial German Navy, and the longest-serving [[dreadnought]]-type ship in any navy.{{sfn|Hough|p=91}}

== Design ==

{{details|Moltke-class battlecruiser}}

''Goeben'' was {{convert|186.6|m|ftin|sp=us}} long, {{convert|29.4|m|ft|abbr=on}} wide, and had a draft of {{convert|9.19|m|ftin|abbr=on}} fully loaded. The ship [[Displacement (ship)|displaced]] {{convert|22,979|t|LT|abbr=on}} normally, and {{convert|25,400|t|LT|abbr=on}} fully loaded. ''Goeben'' was powered by four-shaft [[Parsons Marine Steam Turbine Company|Parsons]] [[steam turbine]]s in two sets and 24 coal-fired Schulz-Thornycroft [[water-tube boiler]]s, which provided a rated {{convert|38,246|kW|shp|order=flip|abbr=on|lk=in}} and a top speed of {{convert|25.5|kn|lk=in}}. At {{convert|14|kn}}, the ship had a range of {{convert|4,120|nmi|lk=in}}.{{sfn|Staff|p=12}}

The ship was armed with a main battery of ten [[28 cm SK L/50 gun]]s in five twin gun turrets. Her secondary armament consisted of twelve [[15 cm SK L/45|15&nbsp;cm SK L/45 guns]] in [[casemate]]s in the central portion of the ship and twelve [[8.8 cm SK L/45 naval gun|8.8&nbsp;cm SK L/45 guns]] in the bow, in the stern, and around the forward [[conning tower]]. She was also equipped with four 50&nbsp;cm (20&nbsp;in) submerged [[torpedo tube]]s.{{sfn|Staff|p=12}}

==Service history ==
The Imperial German Navy (''Kaiserliche Marine'') ordered ''Goeben'', the third German battlecruiser, on 8 April 1909 under the provisional name "H" from the [[Blohm & Voss]] shipyard in Hamburg, under construction number 201. Her keel was laid on 19 August; the hull was completed and the ship was launched on 28 March 1911. [[Fitting-out]] work followed, and she was commissioned into the German Navy on 2 July 1912.{{sfn|Staff|p=12}}

When the [[First Balkan War]] broke out in October 1912, the [[German General Staff]] determined that a naval Mediterranean Division (''Mittelmeer-Division'') was needed to project German power in the Mediterranean, and thus dispatched ''Goeben'' and the light cruiser {{SMS|Breslau||2}} to [[Constantinople]]. The two ships left [[Kiel]] on 4 November and arrived on 15 November 1912. Beginning in April 1913, ''Goeben'' visited many Mediterranean ports including [[Venice]], [[Pula|Pola]], and [[Naples]], before sailing into [[Albania|Albanian waters]]. Following this trip, ''Goeben'' returned to Pola and remained there from 21 August to 16 October for maintenance.{{sfn|Staff|p=18}}

On 29 June 1913, the [[Second Balkan War]] broke out and the Mediterranean Division was retained in the area. On 23 October 1913, [[Wilhelm Souchon|''Konteradmiral'' Souchon]] assumed command of the squadron. ''Goeben'' and ''Breslau'' continued their activities in the Mediterranean, and visited some 80 ports before the outbreak of World War I.{{sfn|Staff|p=18}} The navy made plans to replace ''Goeben'' with her sister {{SMS|Moltke||2}}, but the [[assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand of Austria]] in Sarajevo, Bosnia, on 28 June 1914 and the subsequent rise in tensions between the Great Powers made this impossible.{{sfn|Staff|p=15}}

After the assassination, Admiral Souchon assessed that war was imminent between the [[Central Powers]] and the [[Triple Entente]], and ordered his ships to make for Pola for repairs.{{sfn|Staff|p=18}} Engineers came from Germany to work on the ship.{{sfn|Halpern|p=51}} ''Goeben'' had 4,460 boiler tubes replaced, among other repairs. Upon completion, the ships departed for Messina.{{sfn|Staff|p=18}}

=== World War I ===

==== Pursuit of ''Goeben'' and ''Breslau'' ====

{{main article|Pursuit of Goeben and Breslau}}
[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 134-D0004, Großer Kreuzer Goeben.jpg|thumb|''Goeben'' in port, date unknown|alt=A large, light gray warship sits in harbor, the two forward gun barrels are turned slightly to the left.]]
[[Kaiser Wilhelm II]] had ordered that in the event of war, ''Goeben'' and ''Breslau'' should either conduct raids in the western Mediterranean to prevent the return of French troops from North Africa to Europe,{{sfn|Halpern|p=51}} or break out into the Atlantic and attempt to return to German waters, on the squadron commander's discretion.{{sfn|Herwig|p=153}}  On 3 August 1914, the two ships were en route to Algeria when Souchon received word of the declaration of war against France. ''Goeben'' bombarded [[Skikda|Philippeville]] (now Skikda, Algeria) for about 10 minutes early on 3 August while ''Breslau'' shelled Bône (now [[Annaba]], on the site of the ancient city of Hippo) in accordance with the Kaiser's order.{{sfn|Halpern|p=52}} Admirals [[Alfred von Tirpitz]] and [[Hugo von Pohl]] then transmitted secret orders to Souchon instructing him to sail to [[Constantinople]], in direct contravention of the Kaiser's instructions and without his knowledge.{{sfn|Herwig|p=153}}

Since ''Goeben'' could not reach Constantinople without coaling, Souchon headed for Messina. The Germans encountered the British battlecruisers {{HMS|Indefatigable|1909|6}} and {{HMS|Indomitable|1907|2}}, but as Germany was not yet at war with Britain, no violence ensued. The British turned to follow ''Goeben'' and ''Breslau'', but the German ships were able to outrun the British, and arrived in Messina by 5 August. Refueling in Messina was complicated by the declaration of Italian neutrality on 2 August. Under international law, combatant ships were permitted only 24 hours in a neutral port.{{sfn|Halpern|p=52}}{{sfn|Second Hague Convention, Section 13}} Sympathetic Italian naval authorities in the port allowed ''Goeben'' and ''Breslau'' to remain in port for around 36 hours while the ships coaled from a German [[Collier (ship type)|collier]].{{sfn|Bennett|p=31}} Despite the additional time, ''Goeben''{{'}}s fuel stocks were not sufficient to permit the voyage to Constantinople, so Souchon arranged to rendezvous with another collier in the [[Aegean Sea]].{{sfn|Halpern|p=52}} The French fleet remained in the western Mediterranean, since the French naval commander in the Mediterranean, [[Augustin Boué de Lapeyrère|Admiral Lapeyrère]], was convinced the Germans would either attempt to escape to the Atlantic or join the Austrians in Pola.{{sfn|Halpern|pp=55–56}}

[[File:Großer Kreuzer SMS Goeben.jpg|left|thumb|Prewar postcard depicting ''Goeben'']]
Souchon's two ships departed Messina early on 6 August through the southern entrance to [[Strait of Messina|the strait]] and headed for the eastern Mediterranean. The two British battlecruisers were 100&nbsp;miles away, while a third, {{HMS|Inflexible|1907|2}}, was coaling in [[Bizerta]], Tunisia. The only British naval force in Souchon's way was the 1st Cruiser Squadron,{{sfn|Bennett|p=33}} which consisted of the four [[armored cruisers]] {{HMS|Defence|1907|2}}, {{HMS|Black Prince|1904|2}}, {{HMS|Duke of Edinburgh||2}} and {{HMS|Warrior|1905|2}} under the command of Rear Admiral [[Ernest Troubridge]].{{sfn|Bennett|p=27}} The Germans headed initially towards the Adriatic in a [[feint]]; the move misled Troubridge, who sailed to intercept them in the mouth of the Adriatic. After realizing his mistake, Troubridge reversed course and ordered the light cruiser {{HMS|Dublin|1912|2}} and two destroyers to launch a torpedo attack on the Germans. ''Breslau''{{'}}s lookouts spotted the ships, and in the darkness, she and ''Goeben'' evaded their pursuers undetected. Troubridge broke off the chase early on 7 August, convinced that any attack by his four older armored cruisers against ''Goeben''—armed with her larger 28&nbsp;cm guns—would be suicidal.{{sfn|Bennett|pp=33–34}} Souchon's journey to Constantinople was now clear.{{sfn|Halpern|p=56}}

''Goeben'' refilled her coal bunkers off the island of Donoussa near [[Naxos Island|Naxos]].{{sfn|Halpern|p=56}} During the afternoon of 10 August, the two ships entered the [[Dardanelles]]. They were met by an Ottoman [[picket boat]], which guided them through to the [[Sea of Marmara]].{{sfn|Bennett|pp=35–36}} To circumvent neutrality requirements, the [[Sublime Porte|Ottoman government]] proposed that the ships be transferred to its ownership "by means of a fictitious sale."{{sfn|Hamilton & Herwig|p=164}} Before the Germans could approve this, the Ottomans announced on 11 August that they had purchased the ships for 80 million [[German gold mark|Marks]]. In a formal ceremony the two ships were commissioned in the [[Ottoman Navy]] on 16 August. On 23 September, Souchon accepted an offer to command the Turkish fleet. ''Goeben'' was renamed ''Yavuz Sultan Selim'' and ''Breslau'' was renamed {{ship|Ottoman cruiser|Midilli||2}}; their German crews donned Ottoman uniforms and [[Fez (hat)|fezzes]].{{sfn|Halpern|pp=57–58}}

==== Black Sea operations ====

===== 1914 =====
[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 134-B0024, Stenia, Bosporus, Kreuzer Goeben.jpg|thumb|''Yavuz'' at [[Istinye|Istinye Bay]] on the European shoreline of the [[Bosphorus]] in [[Istanbul]].|alt=A large warship is tied to the dock in a narrow channel of water.]]

On 29 October ''Yavuz'' bombarded [[Sevastopol]] in her first operation against Imperial Russia, though the Ottoman Empire was not yet at war with the Entente; [[Battle of Odessa (1914)|Souchon conducted the operation]] to force Turkey into the war on the side of Germany. A {{convert|25.4|cm|in|abbr=on|0}} shell struck the ship in the [[aft]]er funnel, but it failed to detonate and did negligible damage.{{sfn|Staff|p=19}} Two other hits inflicted minor damage. The ship and her escorts passed through an inactive Russian minefield during the bombardment.{{sfn|McLaughlin|p=122}} As she returned to Turkish waters, ''Yavuz'' came across the Russian minelayer {{ship|Russian minelayer|Prut||2}} which scuttled herself with 700 mines on board.{{sfn|Langensiepen & Güleryüz|p=44}} During the engagement the escorting Russian destroyer {{ship|Russian destroyer|Lieutenant Pushkin||2}} was damaged by two of ''Yavuz''{{'}}s secondary battery {{convert|15|cm|in|abbr=on}} shells. In response to the bombardment, Russia declared war on 1 November, thus forcing the Ottomans into the wider world war. France and Great Britain bombarded the Turkish fortresses guarding the Dardanelles on 3 November and formally declared war two days later.{{sfn|Staff|p=19}} From this engagement, the Russians drew the conclusion that the entire [[Black Sea Fleet]] would have to remain consolidated so it could not be [[defeat in detail|defeated in detail]] (one ship at a time) by ''Yavuz''.{{sfn|Halpern|p=227}}

''Yavuz'', escorted by ''Midilli'', [[Battle of Cape Sarych|intercepted the Russian Black Sea Fleet]] {{convert|17|nmi}} off the [[Crimea]]n coastline on 18 November as it returned from a bombardment of [[Trabzon|Trebizond]]. Despite the noon hour the conditions were foggy and none of the capital ships were spotted initially. The Black Sea Fleet had experimented with concentrating fire from several ships under the control of one "master" ship before the war, and {{ship|Russian battleship|Evstafi||2}} held her fire until {{ship|Russian battleship|Ioann Zlatoust||2}}, the master ship, could see ''Yavuz''. When the gunnery commands were finally received they showed a range over {{convert|4000|yd}} in excess of ''Evstafi''{{'}}s own estimate of {{convert|7700|yd}}, so ''Evstafi'' opened fire using her own data before ''Yavuz'' turned to fire its [[broadside]].{{sfn|McLaughlin|pp=127–128}} She scored a hit with her first salvo as a 12-inch shell partially penetrated the armor casemate protecting one of ''Yavuz''{{'}}s {{convert|15|cm|adj=on|1|sp=us}} secondary guns. It detonated some of the ready-use ammunition, starting a fire that filled the casemate and killed the entire gun crew.{{sfn|McLaughlin|p=131}} A total of thirteen men were killed and three were wounded.{{sfn|Staff|p=19}}

''Yavuz'' returned fire and hit ''Evstafi'' in the middle funnel; the shell detonated after it passed through the funnel and destroyed the antennae for the fire-control radio, so that ''Evstafi'' could not correct ''Ioann Zlatoust''{{'}}s inaccurate range data. The other Russian ships either used ''Ioann Zlatoust''{{'}}s incorrect data or never saw ''Yavuz'' and failed to register any hits. ''Yavuz'' hit ''Evstafi'' four more times, although one shell failed to detonate,{{sfn|McLaughlin|p=131}} before [[Rear Admiral]] [[Wilhelm Souchon]] decided to break contact after 14 minutes of combat.{{sfn|McLaughlin|pp=129–130}} The four hits out of nineteen {{convert|28|cm|in|abbr=on}} shells fired killed 34 men and wounded 24.{{sfn|McLaughlin|pp=131, 133}}

The following month, on 5–6 December, ''Yavuz'' and ''Midilli'' provided protection for troop transports, and on 10 December, ''Yavuz'' bombarded [[Batum]].{{sfn|Staff|p=19}} On 23 December, ''Yavuz'' and {{ship|Ottoman cruiser|Hamidiye||2}} escorted three transports to Trebizond. While returning from another transport escort operation on 26 December, ''Yavuz'' struck a mine that exploded beneath the conning tower, on the starboard side, about one nautical mile outside the [[Bosphorus]].{{sfn|Halpern|p=228}} The explosion tore a {{convert|50|m2|sqft|adj=on|sp=us}} hole in the ship's hull, but the torpedo bulkhead held. Two minutes later, ''Yavuz'' struck a second mine on the port side, just forward of the main battery wing [[barbette]]; this tore open a {{convert|64|m2|sqft|adj=on|sp=us}} hole. The bulkhead bowed in {{convert|30|cm|in|abbr=on}} but retained watertight protection of the ship's interior. However, some 600 tons of water flooded the ship.{{sfn|Staff|p=19}} There was no dock in the Ottoman Empire large enough to service ''Yavuz'', so temporary repairs were effected inside steel [[cofferdam]]s, which were pumped out to create a dry work area around the damaged hull. The holes were patched with concrete, which held for several years before more permanent work was necessary.{{sfn|Halpern|p=228}}

===== 1915 =====
Still damaged, ''Yavuz'' sortied from the Bosphorus on 28 January and again on 7 February 1915 to help ''Midilli'' escape the Russian fleet; she also covered the return of the [[protected cruiser]] {{ship|Ottoman cruiser|Hamidiye||2}}. ''Yavuz'' then underwent repair work to the mine damage until May.{{sfn|Halpern|p=228}} On 1 April, with repairs incomplete, ''Yavuz'' left the Bosphorus in company with ''Midilli'' to cover the withdrawal of ''Hamidiye'' and the protected cruiser {{ship|Ottoman cruiser|Mecidiye||2}}, which had been sent to bombard Odessa. Strong currents, however, forced the cruisers {{convert|15|mi}} east to the approaches of the Dnieper-Bug [[Liman (landform)|Liman]] (bay) that led to [[Mykolaiv|Nikolayev]]. As they sailed west after a course correction, ''Mecidiye'' struck a mine and sank, so this attack had to be aborted.{{sfn|Nekrasov|pp=51–52}} After ''Yavuz'' and ''Midilli'' appeared off Sevastopol and sank two cargo steamers, the Russian fleet chased them all day, and detached several destroyers after dusk to attempt a torpedo attack. Only one destroyer, {{ship|Russian destroyer|Gnevny||2}}, was able to close the distance and launch an attack, which missed. ''Yavuz'' and ''Midilli'' returned to the Bosphorus unharmed.{{sfn|Halpern|p=231}}

On 25 April, the same day the Allies [[Gallipoli Campaign|landed at Gallipoli]], Russian naval forces arrived off the Bosphorus and bombarded the forts guarding the strait. Two days later ''Yavuz Sultan Selim'' headed south to the [[Dardanelles]] to bombard Allied troops at Gallipoli, accompanied by the [[pre-dreadnought battleship]] {{ship|Ottoman battleship|Turgut Reis||2}}. They were spotted at dawn from a [[kite balloon]] as they were getting into position. When the first {{convert|15|in|adj=on}} round from the dreadnought {{HMS|Queen Elizabeth|1913|2}} landed close by, ''Yavuz'' moved out of firing position, close to the cliffs, where ''Queen Elizabeth'' could not engage her.{{sfn|Corbett|p=359}} On 30 April ''Yavuz'' tried again, but was spotted from the pre-dreadnought {{HMS|Lord Nelson|1906|2}} which had moved into the Dardanelles to bombard the Turkish headquarters at [[Çanakkale]]. The British ship only managed to fire five rounds before ''Yavuz'' moved out of her line of sight.{{sfn|Corbett|p=370}}

On 1 May, ''Yavuz'' sailed to the Bay of Beikos in the Bosphorus after the Russian fleet bombarded the fortifications at the mouth of the Bosphorus. Around 7 May, ''Yavuz'' sortied from the Bosphorus in search of Russian ships as far as Sevastopol, but found none. Running short on main gun ammunition, she did not bombard Sevastopol. While returning on the morning of 10 May, ''Yavuz''{{'}}s lookouts spotted two Russian pre-dreadnoughts, {{ship|Russian battleship|Tri Sviatitelia||2}} and {{ship|Russian battleship|Panteleimon||2}}, and she opened fire. Within the first ten minutes she had been hit twice, although she was not seriously damaged. Admiral Souchon disengaged and headed for the Bosphorus, pursued by Russian light forces.{{sfn|Langensiepen & Güleryüz|pp=47–48}} Later that month two of the ship's 15&nbsp;cm guns were taken ashore for use there,{{sfn|Staff|p=12}} and the four 8.8&nbsp;cm guns in the aft superstructure were removed at the same time.{{sfn|Campbell|p=23}} Four 8.8&nbsp;cm [[Anti-aircraft warfare|anti-aircraft]] were installed on the aft superstructure by the end of 1915.{{sfn|Brice|p=276}}

[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 134-B0032, Großer Kreuzer Goeben.jpg|thumb|left|''Yavuz'' steaming at full speed|alt=A large warship plows through the water, thick black smoke pouring from its two central smoke stacks.]]

On 18 July, ''Midilli'' struck a mine; the ship took on some {{convert|600|LT|t}} of water and was no longer able to escort coal convoys from [[Zonguldak]] to the Bosphorus. ''Yavuz'' was assigned to the task, and on 10 August she escorted a convoy of five coal transports, along with ''Hamidiye'' and three [[torpedo boat]]s. During transit, the convoy was attacked by the Russian submarine [[Morzh-class submarine|''Tyulen'']], which sank one of the colliers. The following day, ''Tyulen'' and another submarine tried to attack ''Yavuz'' as well, though they were unable to reach a firing position.{{sfn|Halpern|p=234}}

Two Russian destroyers, {{ship|Russian destroyer|Bystry||2}} and {{ship|Russian destroyer|Pronzitelni||2}}, attacked a Turkish convoy escorted by ''Hamidiye'' and two torpedo boats on 5 September. ''Hamidiye''{{'}}s {{convert|15|cm|in|abbr=on}} guns broke down during combat, and the Turks summoned ''Yavuz'', but she arrived too late: the Turkish colliers had already been beached to avoid capture by the Russian destroyers.{{sfn|Halpern|p=234}}

On 21 September, ''Yavuz Sultan Selim'' was again sent out of the Bosphorus to drive off three Russian destroyers which had been attacking Turkish coal ships. Escort missions continued until 14 November, when the submarine {{ship|Russian submarine|Morzh||2}} nearly hit ''Yavuz'' with two torpedoes just outside the Bosphorus. Admiral Souchon decided the risk to the battlecruiser was too great, and suspended the convoy system. In its stead, only those ships fast enough to make the journey from Zonguldak to Constantinople in a single night were permitted; outside the Bosphorus they would be met by torpedo boats to defend them against the lurking submarines.{{sfn|Halpern|p=235}} By the end of the summer, the completion of two new Russian [[dreadnought battleship]]s, {{ship|Russian battleship|Imperatritsa Mariya||2}} and {{ship|Russian battleship|Imperatritsa Ekaterina Velikaya||2}}, further curtailed ''Yavuz''{{'}}s activities.{{sfn|Halpern|p=236}}

===== 1916–17 =====

[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 146-1981-137-08A, Konstantinopel, Besuch Kaiser Wilhelm II..jpg|thumb|[[Wilhelm II, German Emperor|Kaiser Wilhelm II]] visiting ''Yavuz'' during his stay in [[Istanbul]] in October 1917 as a guest of [[Mehmed V|Sultan Mehmed V]], his ally in [[World War I|WWI]].|alt=Several men in military uniforms, some wearing the Turkish Fez, aboard a warship; a large, boxy gun turret is on the right.]]

Admiral Souchon sent ''Yavuz'' to Zonguldak on 8 January to protect an approaching empty collier from Russian destroyers in the area, but the Russians sank the transport ship before ''Yavuz'' arrived. On the return trip to the Bosphorus, ''Yavuz'' encountered ''Imperatritsa Ekaterina''. The two ships engaged in a brief artillery duel, beginning at a range of 18,500&nbsp;meters. ''Yavuz'' turned to the southwest, and in the first four minutes of the engagement, fired five salvos from her main guns. Neither ship scored any hits, though shell splinters from near misses struck ''Yavuz''.{{sfn|Halpern|p=237}} Though nominally much faster than ''Imperatritsa Ekaterina'', the Turkish battlecruiser's bottom was badly fouled and her propeller shafts were in poor condition. This made it difficult for ''Yavuz'' to escape from the powerful Russian battleship, which was reported to have reached {{convert|23.5|kn|abbr=on}}.{{sfn|Campbell|p=26}}{{efn|{{harvnb|Langensiepen & Güleryüz}} make no mention of this engagement.}}

Russian forces were making significant gains into Ottoman territory during the [[Caucasus Campaign]]. In an attempt to prevent further advances by the Russian army, ''Yavuz'' rushed 429 officers and men, a mountain artillery battery, machine gun and aviation units, 1,000 rifles, and 300 cases of munitions to [[Trabzon|Trebizond]] on 4 February.{{sfn|Halpern|p=241}} On 4 March, the Russian navy landed a detachment of some 2,100 men, along with mountain guns and horses, on either side of the port of [[Pazar, Rize|Atina]]. The Turks were caught by surprise and forced to evacuate.{{sfn|Halpern|p=240}} Another landing took place at Kavata Bay, some 5&nbsp;miles east of Trebizond, in June.{{sfn|Halpern|pp=243–244}} In late June, the Turks counterattacked and penetrated around 20&nbsp;miles into the Russian lines. ''Yavuz'' and ''Midilli'' conducted a series of coastal operations to support the Turkish attacks. On 4 July, ''Yavuz'' shelled the port of [[Tuapse]], where she sank a steamer and a motor [[schooner]].{{sfn|Halpern|pp=244–245}} The Turkish ships sailed northward to circle back behind the Russians before the two Russian dreadnoughts left [[Sevastopol]] to try to attack them. They then returned to the Bosphorus,{{sfn|Halpern|p=245}} where ''Yavuz'' was docked for repairs to her [[propeller shaft]]s until September.{{sfn|Langensiepen & Güleryüz|p=51}}

The coal shortage continued to worsen until Admiral Souchon was forced to suspend operations by ''Yavuz'' and ''Midilli'' through 1917.{{sfn|Halpern|p=248}} After an armistice between Russia and the Ottoman Empire was signed in December 1917 following the [[Russian Revolution (1917)|Bolshevik revolution]], formalized in the [[Treaty of Brest-Litovsk]] in March 1918, coal started to arrive again from eastern Turkey.{{sfn|Halpern|p=255}}

===== 1918 =====
[[File:SMS Goeben in Sevastopol.png|thumb|''Yavuz'' in [[Sevastopol]], 1918]]

On 20 January 1918, ''Yavuz'' and ''Midilli'' left the Dardanelles under the command of Vice Admiral Rebeur-Paschwitz, who had replaced Souchon the previous September. Rebeur-Paschwitz's intention was to draw Allied naval forces away from Palestine in support of Turkish forces there.{{sfn|Halpern|p=255}} Outside the straits, in the course of what became known as the [[Battle of Imbros (1918)|Battle of Imbros]], ''Yavuz'' surprised and sank the [[Monitor (warship)|monitors]] {{HMS|Raglan||2}} and {{HMS|M28||2}} which were at anchor and unsupported by the pre-dreadnoughts that should have been guarding them. Rebeur-Paschwitz then decided to proceed to the port of [[Mudros]]; there the British pre-dreadnought battleship {{HMS|Agamemnon|1906|2}} was raising steam to attack the Turkish ships.{{sfn|Buxton|pp=36–37}} While en route, ''Midilli'' struck several mines and sank;{{sfn|Halpern|p=255}} ''Yavuz'' hit three mines as well.{{sfn|Gardiner & Gray|p=152}} Retreating to the Dardanelles and followed by the British destroyers {{HMS|Lizard|1911|6}} and {{HMS|Tigress|1911|2}},{{sfn|Buxton|p=38}} she was intentionally beached near Nagara Point just outside the Dardanelles.{{sfn|Halpern|p=255}} The British attacked ''Yavuz'' with bombers from No. 2 Wing of the [[Royal Naval Air Service]] while she was grounded and hit her twice, but the bombs from the light aircraft were not heavy enough to do any serious damage. The monitor {{HMS|M17||2}} attempted to shell ''Yavuz'' on the evening of 24 January, but only managed to fire ten rounds before withdrawing to escape the Turkish artillery fire.{{sfn|Hownam-Meek et al.}} The submarine {{HMS|E14||2}} was sent to destroy the damaged ship, but was too late;{{sfn|Halpern|pp=255–256}} the old ex-German pre-dreadnought {{ship|Ottoman battleship|Turgut Reis||2}} had towed ''Yavuz'' off and returned her to the safety of Constantinople.{{sfn|Staff|p=20}} ''Yavuz'' was crippled by the extensive damage; cofferdams were again built around the hull,{{sfn|Halpern|p=256}} and repairs lasted from 7 August to 19 October.{{sfn|Staff|p=20}}

''Yavuz'' escorted the members of the Ottoman Armistice Commission to [[Odessa]] on 30 March 1918, after the [[Treaty of Brest-Litovsk]] was signed. After returning to Constantinople she sailed in May to Sevastopol where she had her hull cleaned and some leaks repaired. ''Yavuz'' and several destroyers sailed for [[Novorossiysk]] on 28 June to intern the remaining Soviet warships, but they had already been scuttled when the Turkish ships arrived. The destroyers remained, but ''Yavuz'' returned to Sevastopol. On 14 July the ship was [[laid up]] for the rest of the war.{{sfn|Langensiepen & Güleryüz|p=54}} While in Sevastopol, dockyard workers scraped fouling from the ship's bottom. ''Yavuz'' subsequently returned to Constantinople, where from 7 August to 19 October a concrete cofferdam was installed to repair one of the three areas damaged by mines.{{sfn|Campbell|p=26}}

The German navy formally transferred ownership of the vessel to the Turkish government on 2 November.{{sfn|Halpern|p=258}} According to the terms of the [[Treaty of Sèvres]] between the Ottoman Empire and the Western Allies, ''Yavuz'' was to have been handed over to the [[Royal Navy]] as war reparations. After the [[Turkish War of Independence]], led by [[Mustafa Kemal Atatürk]], the Treaty of Sèvres was discarded, and the [[Treaty of Lausanne]] was signed in its place in 1923. Under this treaty, the new Turkish republic regained possession of much its fleet, including ''Yavuz''.{{sfn|Gardiner & Gray|p=388}}

=== Post-war service ===
During the 1920s, a commitment to refurbish ''Yavuz'' as the centerpiece of the new country's fleet was the only constant element of the various naval policies which were put forward.{{sfn|Güvenç & Barlas|p=7}}  The battlecruiser remained in [[İzmit]] until 1926, in a neglected state:{{sfn|Gardiner & Gray|p=391}}{{sfn|Whitley|p=241}}{{sfn|Worth|p=271}} only two of her boilers worked, she could not steer or steam, and she still had two unrepaired scars from the mine damage in 1918. Enough money was raised to allow the purchase of a new {{convert|26000|t|LT|adj=on|sp=us}} [[floating dry dock|floating dock]] from Germany, as ''Yavuz'' could not be towed anywhere without risk of her sinking in rough seas.{{sfn|Brice|p=277}} The French company Atelier et Chantiers de St. Nazaire-Penhöet was contracted in December 1926 to oversee the subsequent refit, which was carried out by the [[Gölcük Naval Shipyard]].{{sfn|Whitley|p=241}} Work proceeded over three years (1927–1930); it was delayed when several compartments of the dock collapsed while being pumped out. ''Yavuz'' was slightly damaged before she could be refloated and the dock had to be repaired before the repair work could begin. The Minister of Marine, Ihsan Bey (İhsan Eryavuz), was convicted of embezzlement in the resulting investigation.{{sfn|Brice|p=277}} Other delays were caused by fraud charges which resulted in the abolition of the Ministry of Marine. The Turkish Military's Chief of Staff, [[Fevzi Çakmak|Marshal Fevzi]], opposed naval construction and slowed down all naval building programs following the fraud charges. Intensive work on the battlecruiser only began after the Greek Navy conducted a large-scale naval exercise off Turkey in September 1928 and the Turkish Government perceived a need to counter Greece's naval superiority.{{sfn|Barlas & Güvenç|p=152}} The Turks also ordered four destroyers and two submarines from Italian shipyards.{{sfn|Rohwer & Monakov|p=30}} The Greek Government proposed a 10-year "holiday" from naval building modeled on the [[Washington Naval Treaty|Washington Treaty]] when it learned that ''Yavuz'' was to be brought back into service, though it reserved the right to build two new cruisers. The Turkish Government rejected this proposal, and claimed that the ship was intended to counter the growing strength of the [[Soviet Navy]] in the Black Sea.{{sfn|Güvenç & Barlas|p=10}}

[[File:Turkish battlecruiser Yavuz at Istanbul in 1947.jpg|thumb|''Yavuz'' in Istanbul, 1947]]
[[File:A.screw.of.yavuz.jpg|thumb|The [[propeller]] of Yavuz in Gölcük]]

Over the course of the refit, the mine damage was repaired,{{sfn|Gardiner & Gray|p=152}} her displacement was increased to {{convert|23100|t|LT|abbr=on}}, and the hull was slightly reworked. She was reduced in length by a half meter but her beam increased by {{convert|10|cm|0|abbr=on}}. ''Yavuz'' was equipped with new boilers and a French fire control system for her main battery guns. Two of the 15&nbsp;cm guns were removed from their casemate positions.{{sfn|Gardiner & Gray|p=391}} Her armor protection was not upgraded to take the lessons of the [[Battle of Jutland]] into account, and she had only {{convert|2|in|cm}} of armor above her magazines.{{sfn|Worth|p=271}} ''Yavuz'' was recommissioned in 1930, resuming her role as [[flagship]] of the Turkish Navy,{{sfn|Brice|p=278}} and performed better than expected in her speed trials; her subsequent gunnery and fire control trials were also successful. The four destroyers, which were needed to protect the battlecruiser, entered service between 1931 and 1932; their performance never met the design specifications.{{sfn|Güvenç & Barlas|pp=19–20}} In response to ''Yavuz''{{'}}s return to service, the Soviet Union transferred the battleship {{ship|Soviet battleship|Parizhskaya Kommuna||2}} and light cruiser {{ship|Soviet cruiser|Profintern||2}} from the Baltic in late 1929 to ensure that the Black Sea Fleet retained parity with the Turkish Navy.{{sfn|Rohwer & Monakov|p=30}} The Greek Government also responded by ordering two destroyers.{{sfn|Barlas & Güvenç|p=155}}

In 1933, she took [[List of Prime Ministers of Turkey|Prime Minister]] [[İsmet İnönü]] from [[Varna]] to [[Istanbul]] and carried the [[Reza Shah|Shah of Iran]] from [[Trabzon|Trebizond]] to [[Samsun]] the following year.{{sfn|Brice|p=278}} ''Yavuz Sultan Selim'' had her name officially shortened to ''Yavuz Sultan'' in 1930 and then to ''Yavuz'' in 1936.{{sfn|Langensiepen & Güleryüz|p=142}} Another short refit was conducted in 1938, and in November that year she carried the remains of [[Mustafa Kemal Atatürk]] from Istanbul to İzmit.{{sfn|Gardiner & Gray|p=391}}{{sfn|Whitley|p=241}} She and the other ships of the navy were considered outdated by the British Naval Attache by 1937, partly due to their substandard anti-aircraft armament, but in 1938 the Turkish government began planning to expand the force.{{sfn|Deringil|p=35}} Under these plans the surface fleet was to comprise two 10,000 ton cruisers and twelve destroyers. ''Yavuz'' would be retained until the second cruiser was commissioned in 1945, and the navy expected to build a 23,000 ton ship between 1950 and 1960. The naval building program did not come about, as the foreign shipyards which were to build the ships concentrated on the needs of their own nations leading up to [[World War II]].{{sfn|Güvenç & Barlas|pp=27–28}}

''Yavuz'' remained in service throughout World War II. In November 1939 she and ''Parizhskaya Kommuna'' were the only capital ships in the Black Sea region, and ''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'' magazine reported that ''Yavuz'' was superior to the Soviet ship because the latter was in poor condition.{{sfn|Eliot}} In 1941, her anti-aircraft battery was strengthened to four {{convert|88|mm|in|abbr=on}} guns, ten {{convert|40|mm|in|abbr=on}} guns, and four {{convert|20|mm|in|abbr=on}} guns. These were later increased to twenty-two 40&nbsp;mm guns and twenty-four 20&nbsp;mm guns.{{sfn|Gardiner & Gray|p=391}} On 5 April 1946, the American battleship {{USS|Missouri|BB-63|6}}, light cruiser {{USS|Providence|CLG-6|2}}, and destroyer {{USS|Power|DD-839|2}} arrived in Istanbul to return the remains of Turkish ambassador [[Münir Ertegün]].{{sfn|Stillwell|pp=99–101}} ''Yavuz'' greeted the ships in the Bosphorus, where she and ''Missouri'' exchanged 19-gun salutes.{{sfn|Stillwell|p=102}}

After 1948, the ship was stationed in either İzmit{{sfn|Gardiner & Gray|p=391}} or [[Gölcük (District), Kocaeli|Gölcük]].{{sfn|Whitley|p=241}} She was decommissioned from active service on 20 December 1950 and [[:wikt:stricken|stricken]] from the Navy register on 14 November 1954.{{sfn|Gardiner & Gray|p=391}}{{sfn|Whitley|p=241}} When Turkey joined [[NATO]] in 1952, the ship was assigned the [[hull number]] B70.{{sfn|Sturton|p=147}} The Turkish government offered to sell the ship to the West German government in 1963 as a [[museum ship]], but the offer was declined.{{sfn|Gardiner & Gray|p=391}} Turkey sold the ship to M.K.E. Seyman in 1971 for [[ship breaking|scrapping]].{{sfn|Whitley|p=241}} She was towed to the breakers on 7 June 1973, and the work was completed in February 1976.{{sfn|Gardiner & Gray|p=391}}{{sfn|Whitley|p=241}} By the time of her disposal she was the last dreadnought in existence outside the United States.{{sfn|Willmott|p=220}}

